The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, June 19, 2004 				 Gesco picks up 38.64% in P amp; Travel
 OUR CORRESPONDENTMumbai, June 18: GE Shipping (Gesco) has increased its stake in P amp; Travel India Ltd (Potil)  a move that will make the latter a subsidiary of the shipping major.																								The company has acquired 13.52 lakh shares, representing 38.64 per cent of Potils equity, from P amp; Cruises B. V. (P amp;), GE Shipping informed the stock exchanges.																								P amp; liquidated its entire shareholding of 21.25 lakh shares in Potil. With this acquisition, GE Shippings holding increased to 63.64 per cent, making Potil its subsidiary, a company statement said.																								While GE Shipping did not provide details on the cost of acquisition, a company spokesperson said the stake was bought to bring down business tour costs of its employees.																								According to sources, Potil caters to the travel needs of large companies and individuals. It has been offering an integrated travel service portfolio, encompassing total solutions and value-added services. It was set up as part of the expansion of the P amp; network in the country more than five years ago.																								It has been offering leisure products, including cruises and a wide range of customised packages of theme and adventure holidays. Potil also has a cargo set-up in Bangalore offering freight forwarding.																								On the Bombay Stock Exchange today, the GE Shipping scrip opened at Rs 121.90, shot up to a high of Rs 122.90 and ended at Rs 121.20. Over 2.15 lakh shares were transacted in 1,972 trades.																								GE Shipping recently reported a 98 per cent rise in net profit for the fourth quarter of the year ended March 31, 2004 at Rs 184.77 crore compared with Rs 93.11 crore in the corresponding period last year. 																								The growth was spurred by high freight rates. In 2003-04, the companys net profit jumped to Rs 471.13 crore from Rs 227.29 crore and income shot up to Rs 1,426.35 crore from Rs 1,007.15 crore in 2002-03.
